{"key":"post-13683840","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13683840</id>\n<content>Oyster producers often use vertical straw logs to get more substrates crammed into less space.&amp;nbsp; The drawback is that your moisture is pulled by gravity to the bottom of the log, saturating it and starving the top of the log for moisture.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Also, more than half the weight of the log is usually sitting on the floor.&amp;nbsp; The cable from above is mostly to prevent the log from tipping over.&amp;nbsp; You can do cubes this way, but you need to cut a small circle around each pin that forms.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;That's why I prefer to sit them on tables or shelves, unwrapped.&lt;br /&gt;RR&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/10-31/123093301-P_ostreatus_straw_log-discarded.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/10-31/123093301-thumb_P_ostreatus_straw_log-discarded.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13684307</next>\n<prev>13683768</prev>\n<first>13683768</first>\n<last>18482889</last>\n<when>1293324364</when>\n<utime>12/26/10 02:46 AM</utime>\n</post>"}